english:
  title: Song of the Young Blade
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In youth, I never took to books,
    Instead I mastered the sword to match ten thousand men.
    My companions were all like Jing Ke and Nie Zheng—
    We haunted the avenues of Chang'an.

    A dagger hung at my waist,
    Flashing like purple lightning down the streets.
    I struck men in the market square at noon,
    Avenging wrongs, heedless of my own life.

    Last year I answered the call to arms,
    Rode west on horseback to strike the barbarian hordes.
    Leading the way across the desert sands,
    I commanded the wind and clouds themselves.

    Like an old hawk stretching its wings,
    I scattered the birds in startled flight.
    I swept clean every den of beast and tiger,
    Returned to the capital singing songs of victory.

    My deeds seemed the work of heaven's hand.
    When offered rank and crimson sash, I refused.
    Now I hide away in my old butcher shop,
    Gathering reckless gamblers to share my days.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jing Ke and Nie Zheng were legendary assassins of ancient China, representing the idealized wandering swordsman.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'purple lightning dagger' suggests both the weapon's beauty and its swift, deadly nature.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem's final twist—rejecting honors to return to humble obscurity—reflects the Daoist ideal of withdrawal from worldly ambition.
